Q5: partly based on intuition about likely means and SD's in both conditions, and partly based on a random number generator. in the number generator i gave the min and max of the numbers based on what numbers i used for one condition/gender. Also a couple of decimals were randomly generated.
Let's see first whether you can detect it's fake. ;)

I simulated normally distributed data for the two conditions based on the data in the paper of Jacowitz &  Kahneman. See the R code below as an example. /  / I'm not sure if in the end this was the best method, since the simulated data contains impossible values. I'm not sure if you can see this in the summary statistics. /  /  / # san francisco - new york /  / n1 <- 53 / n2 <- 47 /  / low <- round(rnorm(n1,2600,1200),0) / high <- round(rnorm(n2,4000,1500),0) /  / low_gender <- sample(c("male","female"),n1,replace=TRUE) / high_gender <- sample(c("male","female"),n2,replace=TRUE) /  / data <- data.frame(estimate=c(low,high), /                    condition=c(rep("low",n1),rep("high",n2)), /                    gender=c(low_gender,high_gender)) /  / summary(aov(lm(estimate~condition,data=data))) / summary(aov(lm(estimate~gender,data=data))) / summary(aov(lm(estimate~condition*gender,data=data))) /  / # low anchor /  / table(data$gender[data$condition=="low"]) /  / mean(data$estimate[data$gender=="male" & data$condition=="low"]) / mean(data$estimate[data$gender=="female" & data$condition=="low"]) /  / sd(data$estimate[data$gender=="male" & data$condition=="low"]) / sd(data$estimate[data$gender=="female" & data$condition=="low"]) /  / # high anchor /  / table(data$gender[data$condition=="high"]) /  / mean(data$estimate[data$gender=="male" & data$condition=="high"]) / mean(data$estimate[data$gender=="female" & data$condition=="high"]) /  / sd(data$estimate[data$gender=="male" & data$condition=="high"]) / sd(data$estimate[data$gender=="female" & data$condition=="high"])
